WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.627 --> 00:00:13.384
At age 44, Xie Qiuping cut her hair
for the first time in over three decades.

00:00:14.177 --> 00:00:18.347
At the time, her impressive locks
extended over five meters—

00:00:18.723 --> 00:00:22.560
earning the Guinness World Record
for the world's longest hair.

00:00:23.770 --> 00:00:25.813
But even with this record-setting feat,

00:00:26.355 --> 00:00:30.026
her hair might not have reached
its maximum possible length.

00:00:30.735 --> 00:00:34.739
So just how long can human hair
actually grow?

00:00:35.865 --> 00:00:37.992
To get to the bottom of this question,

00:00:37.992 --> 00:00:40.828
let's start at the bottom
of a hair follicle.

00:00:41.454 --> 00:00:45.792
Follicles are tube-shaped structures
nestled roughly half a centimeter

00:00:45.792 --> 00:00:47.418
below the skin's surface.

00:00:47.710 --> 00:00:50.421
At their base is what's
called the hair bulb,

00:00:50.588 --> 00:00:53.966
and it contains rapidly
dividing matrix cells.

00:00:54.425 --> 00:00:59.222
As they divide, these develop into
specialized hair cells called trichocytes,

00:00:59.347 --> 00:01:03.684
which harden as they fill themselves
with cable-like keratin proteins.

00:01:03.935 --> 00:01:06.104
As more and more trichocytes are produced,

00:01:06.104 --> 00:01:10.650
they form a strand of hair that emerges
from the follicle and grows upwards.

00:01:11.275 --> 00:01:13.778
All the hair on your body grows this way,

00:01:13.778 --> 00:01:18.116
but not all hair will grow
to the same length, shape, or color.

00:01:18.574 --> 00:01:21.702
Those properties are determined
by yet another type of cell

00:01:21.702 --> 00:01:24.997
within the hair bulb:
the fibroblast.

00:01:25.498 --> 00:01:29.877
Fibroblasts instruct the matrix cells
to grow specific kinds of hair

00:01:29.877 --> 00:01:31.462
for each part of the body.

00:01:31.838 --> 00:01:35.883
This is why doctors doing hair implants
usually use follicles

00:01:35.883 --> 00:01:37.677
from the same body part,

00:01:37.885 --> 00:01:40.346
though they'll sometimes change things up.

00:01:40.763 --> 00:01:44.851
For example, eyelashes are some
of the shortest hairs on your body

00:01:44.851 --> 00:01:47.353
at an average length of one centimeter.

00:01:47.603 --> 00:01:52.942
So to give people longer eyelashes,
doctors might implant scalp follicles,

00:01:52.984 --> 00:01:56.529
which grow at a rate
of about 15 centimeters per year.

00:01:56.946 --> 00:02:00.449
So these patients will have to trim
their new lashes regularly

00:02:00.449 --> 00:02:03.327
to avoid a blinding curtain of hair.

00:02:04.495 --> 00:02:07.373
In general, our follicles
are very resilient.

00:02:07.373 --> 00:02:10.543
Even if you pluck hair out
with your fingers or some wax,

00:02:10.626 --> 00:02:14.881
you’ll likely only damage matrix cells,
not fibroblasts.

00:02:15.173 --> 00:02:18.134
So given time, those hair bulbs
will repair themselves

00:02:18.134 --> 00:02:20.178
and begin producing new hair.

00:02:20.344 --> 00:02:24.557
However, each strand of hair
will only grow for so long.

00:02:25.099 --> 00:02:28.352
We don't fully understand
how follicles measure time,

00:02:28.352 --> 00:02:33.065
but in most cases they'll stop
growing a strand after 5 to 7 years.

00:02:33.482 --> 00:02:37.153
This means that at the rate
of 15 centimeters a year,

00:02:37.361 --> 00:02:41.199
the average person’s scalp hair
could reach a maximum length

00:02:41.365 --> 00:02:42.825
of around one meter.

00:02:43.993 --> 00:02:48.581
The precise duration and speed of
hair growth varies from person to person

00:02:48.623 --> 00:02:52.543
depending on genetics, hormones,
and various health conditions,

00:02:52.793 --> 00:02:57.006
and it’s difficult to know exactly what
combination of these factors

00:02:57.089 --> 00:03:00.176
let Xie Quiping reach her record.

00:03:00.968 --> 00:03:05.348
But however long your locks may be,
when a follicle stops growing,

00:03:05.348 --> 00:03:09.227
the hair falls out—
shedding from our heads slowly,

00:03:09.435 --> 00:03:12.605
or in clumps during showers
and hair brushing.

00:03:13.231 --> 00:03:17.526
After a hair is lost, fibroblasts will
trigger the growth of a new strand

00:03:17.526 --> 00:03:20.196
to fill out your scalp— usually.

00:03:20.613 --> 00:03:23.574
As we age, follicles run
out of certain cell types,

00:03:23.574 --> 00:03:26.077
which can lead to changes in hair growth.

00:03:26.244 --> 00:03:31.666
For example, when they run out of 
pigment-producing melanocyte stem cells,

00:03:31.832 --> 00:03:34.585
follicles begin producing gray hairs.

00:03:34.961 --> 00:03:39.382
And since there are only a handful
of melanocyte stem cells per follicle

00:03:39.382 --> 00:03:40.508
to begin with,

00:03:40.508 --> 00:03:43.719
they tend to run out relatively early
in a person’s life.

00:03:44.512 --> 00:03:48.140
Similarly, when follicles run
out of epithelial stem cells,

00:03:48.140 --> 00:03:51.978
they begin to shrink and grow
shorter, thinner strands

00:03:52.061 --> 00:03:54.939
before eventually shutting down
production altogether.

00:03:55.231 --> 00:03:57.275
This is what leads to baldness,

00:03:57.275 --> 00:04:00.444
though the condition can also be
accelerated by testosterone,

00:04:00.444 --> 00:04:03.239
which can prevent
fibroblasts’ instructions

00:04:03.239 --> 00:04:05.616
from reaching a follicle’s cells.

00:04:06.450 --> 00:04:08.703
While it’s completely natural
for hair growth

00:04:08.703 --> 00:04:10.830
to change over the course of our lives,

00:04:10.830 --> 00:04:14.208
there are ways to take more control
of our scalps.

00:04:14.667 --> 00:04:17.920
Some baldness remedies
remove excess testosterone,

00:04:17.962 --> 00:04:21.549
and special shampoos can address
the coarse, brittle strands

00:04:21.549 --> 00:04:23.801
reported by many people with gray hair.

00:04:24.385 --> 00:04:29.307
Since our bodies already produce hair
at the fastest possible biological speed,

00:04:29.473 --> 00:04:32.435
there's currently no way
to grow hair faster.

00:04:33.019 --> 00:04:37.106
But even if you’re unlikely to beat
Xie Qiuping’s record,

00:04:37.356 --> 00:04:40.860
with time, the right treatments,
and some genetic luck,

00:04:41.152 --> 00:04:44.572
you should be able to grow
some luscious locks of your own.

